<DIV1 N="19" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>XIX. Re|ligious bounden to bodily wark.</HEAD>
<P>&THORN;is is a no&thorn;er, &THORN;at religious men are bounde to bodily warks; &thorn;at semi&thorn; so&thorn; bi &thorn;is. In &thorn;e state of innocens God sett man in paradis of delite, leking &thorn;at he schuld wirk and kep it. In to &thorn;is stat of synne God kest man out of paradise in to &thorn;e &yogh;er&thorn;, &thorn;at he schuld<NOTE PLACE="marg">Gen. i<SUP>o</SUP>.</NOTE> wirk &thorn;e &yogh;er&thorn; &thorn;at he was tane of, and seid to him, In swot of &thorn;i chere<NOTE PLACE="marg">Gen. iii<SUP>o</SUP>.</NOTE> &thorn;u schalt eyt &thorn;i brede, tul &thorn;u turn a&yogh;en in to &thorn;e &yogh;er&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;u art tan of. Also in &thorn;e comaundement, &thorn;u schalt wirk six dayes and do &thorn;i<NOTE PLACE="marg">Exod. xx<SUP>o</SUP>.</NOTE> wark. Also &thorn;us biddi&thorn; &thorn;e apostil, He &thorn;at stale steyle he not, but<NOTE PLACE="marg">Eph. iu<SUP>o</SUP>.</NOTE> more wirk he wi&thorn; his handis &thorn;ing &thorn;at is god, &thorn;at he haue wer of to &yogh;ef to him &thorn;at nedi&thorn;. And eft he sei&thorn;, Bre&thorn;ern, we warn &yogh;ow,<NOTE PLACE="marg">2 Thes. ult.</NOTE> in &thorn;e name of our Lord Ihu Crist, &thorn;at &yogh;e wi&thorn; draw &yogh;ow fro ilk bro&thorn;er going inordinatly, and not after &thorn;e ordre &thorn;at &thorn;ei han tane 
<PB REF="00000170.tif" N="106"> of vs; for &yogh;e wot wel it be howui&thorn; to folow vs, for we han not ben inquiet among &yogh;ow, ne etun ani mannis bred for nou&yogh;t, but wirk|ing in trauel, and werynes, bo&thorn; day and ni&yogh;t, &thorn;at we schuld greue none of &yogh;ow. And &thorn;is we did, not os if we had no power, but &thorn;at we schuld &yogh;ef to &yogh;ow a forme to folow vs; for [wan] we were at &yogh;ow, &thorn;is we wernid &yogh;ow, &thorn;at if any wold not wirk, &thorn;at he eyt not; for we han hard sum a mong &yogh;ow to lif inquiet, no &thorn;ing doing, but leding &thorn;er lif curiously, and we warn &yogh;ow in &thorn;e Lord, &thorn;at &thorn;ei &thorn;at are swilk, wi&thorn; stilnes wirking, eyt &thorn;er bred. And her sei&thorn; Austeyn,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Austeyn.</NOTE> in his book of warkis of monkis, &THORN;e apostil wrowt wi&thorn; his handis &thorn;ingis able to mannis vse honestly, as &thorn;e warkis of carpenteris han hem, werkis of sewars, and of feld telars, and like to &thorn;eis. Pa|triarkis fed bestis; &thorn;e grekis had hem &thorn;at we callen pagaynis, her most honorable philosophurs, sowtars. In &thorn;e kirk, &thorn;is ilk, iustar man, to wam &thorn;e blessid maydun Mari was spowsid, &thorn;at bar Crist, was a carpenter. If &thorn;e patriarkis, &thorn;at were &thorn;e nobliar of &thorn;e Jewis, herdid bestis; philosophurs, &thorn;at were of &thorn;e bettar of pagaynis, wer sowtars; Joseph, &thorn;at was of &thorn;e bettar of cristun, was a carpenter; Poule, after &thorn;at he was apostil, mad tabernaclis; if all &thorn;eis wrout bodily, &thorn;at &thorn;ei schuld not be constreynid to axe &thorn;er necessarijs, or to begge, &thorn;at is &thorn;e same, of wat professioun, or sect, or law, coueit &thorn;ei to be, &thorn;at, a&yogh;en so mani ensaumplis of seyntis, schamun not to beg? And in &thorn;e decre is &thorn;is notid, &thorn;at bi &thorn;e saumple of &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg">Decre.</NOTE> apostle, clerkis may lefuly labor honestly wi&thorn; &thorn;er handis, wil &thorn;ey lefe not Goddis &thorn;at is more profitable. And eft Austeyn sei&thorn;, Wat do<NOTE PLACE="marg">Austeyn.</NOTE> &thorn;ey &thorn;at wil not wirk bodily? I desire to wit to wat &thorn;ing &thorn;ey tent? &THORN;ei sey to prayor, salmis, and redingis, and to &thorn;e word of God, &thorn;at is preching, forso&thorn;, he sei&thorn;, an holy lif. But if we schal not be callid fro &thorn;eis &thorn;ingis, we schal not eyt, ne meytis ar not to be mad redy, ilk day &thorn;at &thorn;ey be tan. But if ned of mannis infirmite con|streyn &thorn;e seruaundis of God to &thorn;eis &thorn;ingis, in certeyn interuallis of tyme, why ordeyn we not sum partis of tyme to kepe &thorn;e apos|tlis 
<PB REF="00000171.tif" N="107"> bidding of wirkyng bodily? Sunnar is &thorn;e prayor hard of o buxum man, &thorn;an ten&thorn;owzand of a dispicer; &thorn;ey seyn hem to tent to lessoun, fynd &thorn;ey not &thorn;er &thorn;at &thorn;e apostil biddi&thorn;, wat ouer&thorn;wartnes is &thorn;is to wil not obey to &thorn;e lesson? Wil &thorn;ey tent &thorn;er to, and &thorn;at &thorn;e lessun be rad &thorn;e lengar to wil not to do &thorn;is &thorn;at is red? Who wot not ilk man to profit so mikil &thorn;e sunnar as he do&thorn; sunnar &thorn;e good &thorn;at he redi&thorn;? Also in &thorn;e rewle of Seynt Frauncis is red:<NOTE PLACE="marg">Ffrauncis.</NOTE> Freris lif &thorn;ey first of &thorn;e labor of &thorn;er handis, &thorn;e secound of &thorn;ing frely &yogh;euun; and wan &thorn;eis suffice not, haue &thorn;ey lefe to axe. And in &thorn;e rewle of Seynt Benet; Idilnes is enemy to &thorn;e soule. And<NOTE PLACE="marg">Benet.</NOTE> &thorn;erfor in certeyn tymis how &thorn;e bre&thorn;ern to be occupied in &thorn;e trauel of her handis. And eft certeyn horis in Goddis lessen, fro pasch tul &thorn;e kalendis of Octobre, goyng vtterly fro &thorn;e first hor tul almost &thorn;e fourt, traueil &thorn;is &thorn;at is necessary fro &thorn;e fourt tul &thorn;e sixte, tent &thorn;ei to &thorn;e lessoun. And if ned, or pouert of &thorn;e place, axe &thorn;at &thorn;ei be occupied to gedre frutis, be &thorn;ei not euy, for &thorn;an are &thorn;ey verely monkis, if &thorn;ey lif of &thorn;e labor of &thorn;er handis, os our fadres and &thorn;e apostlis; &thorn;is &thorn;ere. Now &thorn;an ilk man ley to his hert to &thorn;eis sawis, and o&thorn;er, &thorn;at he see and understond, and after &thorn;e plesing of God perform and fille in dede; schak a wey idilnes, vanite, curiosite, and superfluite, glotany, and lust, and swernes, and o&thorn;er &thorn;ingis &thorn;at bringyn in nede. And reyse he dissolut handis, and dresser ri&yogh;t weies to his feet, and comfort tremeling knees, in to &thorn;e wirkyng of good &thorn;ingis. Snyb he &thorn;e idul, solace hem of litul hert, and be<NOTE PLACE="marg">Sap. iij<SUP>o</SUP>.</NOTE> pesful to all to &thorn;e hert, ffor gloriouse is &thorn;e frut of good labors; for &thorn;e Psalme sei&thorn;, For &thorn;u schalt ete &thorn;e labor of &thorn;i handis, &thorn;u art<NOTE PLACE="marg">Psalm. cxxuij<SUP>o</SUP>.</NOTE> blessid, and wel schal be to &thorn;e. In &thorn;is tyme bi grace, and in tyme to cum bi glory, wan &thorn;e Lord schal bid calle &thorn;e warke men, and pay hem &thorn;er mede, mikil glory and honor for &thorn;er good warkis; and &thorn;an he &thorn;at wyl not now wirk, schal not be punischid wi&thorn; men, but warst of all o&thorn;er, for he breki&thorn; Goddis bidding, and steyli&thorn; a&yogh;en &thorn;e Lordis leue &thorn;is &thorn;at he eyti&thorn;. And so he schal be put wi&thorn; 
<PB REF="00000172.tif" N="108"> &thorn;efis. And for his idilnes wan alle &thorn;ing schal be &yogh;euen to rest, &thorn;an his trauel schal be gynne in sarow.</P>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="30" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>XXX. Begry not leful to re|ligious.</HEAD>
<P>&THORN;is is an o&thorn;er; &thorn;at it is not leful to religious to beg. To &thorn;is I sey &thorn;us; &thorn;ow it be leful to ilk man to beg in nede, neuer&thorn;eles it is [not] leful to ani man wi&thorn; oute nede of releue and iust nede dispicing ri&yogh;tfulnes; noi&thorn;er to gedre him mikil worldly riches, noi&thorn;er wasting his tyme in idilnes, noi&thorn;er &thorn;at he wast himsilf and his goodis, and o&thorn;er mennis, in lustis, and in o&thorn;er veyn curiositeis. And for &thorn;e declaring of &thorn;is mater, I suppose first, &thorn;at begging is tane in diueris maneris, as gostly or bodily; and sum tyme ver|tuously, and sum tyme synfully, and sum tyme peynfully. &THORN;er for &thorn;at to beg understond is sum nedy man to aske, be syde &thorn;e titul of worldly dett, helpe for his releue schewing be signe or bi tokun or be expresse voyce. And &thorn;us it semi&thorn; &thorn;at Crist in manhod, as alle kyngis and princis lifyng, are nedid to beg of God al mi&yogh;ty. And &thorn;us all begging of God gostly godis for relef of hem, and of her bre&thorn;ern, to be releuid of &thorn;er synnis, peynis, and wrechidnes, in case &thorn;ei beg medfuly. Also &thorn;us man leuyng occupacoun about temporal &thorn;ingis, and necessariis of lif, for wark mere profitable and more gostly, and helful to soule, and &thorn;erfor it nedi&thorn; to beg. And to swilk wit, as doctors seyn, is &thorn;is verrified of Crist, &thorn;at &thorn;e Salm sei&thorn;, I am beggar and pore, and nedy, and helples, and swilk o&thorn;er; ffor he taking our kynd, was mad nedy and helples for vs, and &thorn;us he beggid gostly goodis for vs of &thorn;e Fadir. And &thorn;us, as it semi&thorn; to sum of &thorn;e sawis of Seynt Bernard. Wan Ihu was of twelf &yogh;ere<NOTE PLACE="marg">Bernard.</NOTE> age, he dwellid still in Jerusalem after his parentis, &thorn;at he schewyng beggid his liflod fro dore to dore in Jerusalem, for &thorn;at he goyng in &thorn;e cite, schewid his ned to be releuid of &thorn;er defaut &thorn;at hau&yogh;t to haue releuid him, so mi&yogh;t o&thorn;er; ffor far is &thorn;is fro hem &thorn;at beggun wi&thorn; out nede, or wen &thorn;ey mi&yogh;t o&thorn;er wise be susteynid, or for lust, or for o&thorn;er vndu caus beggen baldly. Wylful begging of stalwor&thorn; men is forfendid to ilk cristun man of &thorn;e apostil of Crist, and of 
<PB REF="00000173.tif" N="109"> God himsilf, of Salomon it is vggid, and many fold reprouid of holy doctoris; so &thorn;at &thorn;e almes of &thorn;e pore schal not be &yogh;euen to hem &thorn;at are sufficient and mi&yogh;ty to traueyl, for &thorn;ei &thorn;at are swilk ask almis vniustly, despicyng &thorn;e bidding of &thorn;e apostul, seyng,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Poule.</NOTE> Wirki&thorn; wi&thorn; &yogh;oure handis, as we haue bedun &yogh;ow. And desiri&thorn; no &thorn;ing of no man. And if ani obey not to our word, bi &thorn;e epistil, &thorn;at is to sey, &thorn;at he absten him fro begging, wan he may wi&thorn; bodily traueyl geyt his lyfyng, lok &thorn;at &yogh;e be not men kyd wi&thorn; him, &thorn;at he be counfoundid, and cast out fro alle, wexe schamid, tul he soget<NOTE PLACE="marg">2 Thess.ult.</NOTE> him to &thorn;e biddingis of &thorn;e apostil. And syn no man how to cast out fro comyning of cristun men, but for dedly synne, it folowi&thorn; &thorn;at he synni&thorn; dedly, &thorn;at wilfully, and witingly, bindi&thorn; him to swilk a staat contening traueil, &thorn;at he beg for euer. And it semi&thorn; &thorn;at oon &thorn;us endurid, is not in &thorn;e staat of men to be sauid. Also Salamon sei&thorn;, Lord &yogh;eue me not begrye ne riches, but only neces|<NOTE PLACE="marg">Prou. xxx<SUP>o</SUP>.</NOTE> sariis to my lifing; &thorn;at appily I be not greuid to denay God, or constreyin be nede to steyle, or forsuer &thorn;e name of my Lord God; &thorn;at is, as &thorn;e Glose sei&thorn;, &thorn;at I falle not in to forgeyting of euer<NOTE PLACE="marg">Glose.</NOTE> lasting, for nede, or scarnes of passing &thorn;ingis. Also &thorn;us sei&thorn; God in his law, Vtterly a nedy man begging be &thorn;er not among &yogh;ow.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Deut. xu<SUP>o</SUP>.</NOTE> As if he sey &thorn;us, Sufferi&thorn; not in &yogh;our defaut ani to fal in to so gret defaut &thorn;at he be nedid to beg. And bi &thorn;e same, No man bring himsilf vniustly vn to swilk stat. And wi&thorn; ned it is iust &thorn;at he beg. And &thorn;us sei&thorn; Austeyn vp on &thorn;is word &thorn;at Crist sei&thorn;, Gif<NOTE PLACE="marg">Austeyn.</NOTE> to ilk askyng &thorn;e. If &thorn;u gif not &thorn;at he aski&thorn;, &thorn;u schalt &yogh;eue bettar, whan &thorn;u iustly amendist him &thorn;at aski&thorn; vniustly. And Crist biddi&thorn;,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Luc. xij<SUP>o</SUP>.</NOTE> Selle &thorn;at &yogh;e haue and &yogh;eue almis, &thorn;at is, as &thorn;e Glose sei&thorn;, &thorn;at &yogh;or<NOTE PLACE="marg">Glose.</NOTE> &thorn;ingis left after warkis wi&thorn; &yogh;or handis, &thorn;at &yogh;e haue wer of to lif. Also Austeyn sei&thorn;, Bred is tan a wey more profitable to &thorn;e hungri,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Austeyn.</NOTE> if he siker of lifing despice ritfulnes; &thorn;at is, bred brokun to &thorn;e hungry &thorn;at he desseyuid tent to ri&yogh;twisnes. Also Jerom sei&thorn;, &THORN;ei<NOTE PLACE="marg">Jerom.</NOTE> &thorn;at sufficy to hemsilf, or to be susteynid bi &thorn;e goodis of parentis, 
<PB REF="00000174.tif" N="110"> and namly, but if &thorn;ei clerkis, if &thorn;ei tak gylfuly under color of nede, &thorn;is &thorn;at is dewe to &thorn;e pore, doutles &thorn;ei do sacrilege, and bi misusing of swilk &thorn;ingis &thorn;ei eyte and dring dome to hemsilf. Also Prosper<NOTE PLACE="marg">Prosper.</NOTE> sei&thorn;, &THORN;ei &thorn;at han her owne, if &thorn;ei wil ani &thorn;ing be don to hem, &thorn;ei tak not wi&thorn; out gret synne &thorn;at &thorn;e pore man schuld lif of. As &yogh;eld in almis schal be putt be fore, &thorn;at &thorn;ei only take pore mennis meytis, &thorn;at may not labor ne suffice not. Eft Austeyn sei&thorn;, Wan we may<NOTE PLACE="marg">Austeyn.</NOTE> labor, we how not begging tempt God; &thorn;at as &thorn;us &thorn;at we may of his gift. And sin we lif &thorn;er of, we lif of him gifyng, for he ha&thorn; &yogh;euen &thorn;at we may. Also &thorn;e begging of clerkis is schenschip of<NOTE PLACE="marg">Jerom.</NOTE> bischops; ffor &thorn;us sei&thorn; Jerom, Now syn coueyteis ha&thorn; waxen in &thorn;e kirk, as in &thorn;e empyr of Rome, lawis gon a wey fro &thorn;e prest, and visioun from &thorn;e prophet, al bi power of bischopis name &thorn;at &thorn;ei chalang unlefuly to hem wi&thorn; out &thorn;e kirk. Also &thorn;ei dryue in to &thorn;er vsis al &thorn;at is of dekunis, ne &thorn;ei chalang not &thorn;is only &thorn;at is ascriuid, but &thorn;ei tak a vey all &thorn;ingis fro alle men; &thorn;e vnblessid clerk beggi&thorn; in &thorn;e strete, and boundun vnder seruil werk he aski&thorn; almes opunly of ilk man. And of &thorn;is is he &thorn;e more dispicid of all, &thorn;at he wrechidly desolat is gessid to be fallun iustly to &thorn;is wrechidnes &thorn;o bischopis a lon lowen to &yogh;eftis. Alon he vsi&thorn; ministry. Alon he chalangi&thorn; to him all &thorn;ingis. Alon he assoyli&thorn; o&thorn;er partyes. Alon he sle&thorn; all. And for coueytis of prestis oft risun hatis; &thorn;er for are bischopis accusid of clerkis; &thorn;er of &thorn;e biginning of strif; &thorn;er of &thorn;e cause of detraccoun; &thorn;er of is maad &thorn;e beginning of synne. For so&thorn;, if ilk man in &thorn;is world is bidun to haue sum &thorn;ing, &thorn;at he be content only wi&thorn; possessioun, and tak not o&thorn;er mennis &thorn;ingis, noi&thorn;er &thorn;e feld, noi&thorn;er &thorn;e wyne of &thorn;e pore, nor his wayn, nor his money, nor his frutis, how mikil more he &thorn;at is prest to &thorn;e kirk of God howi&thorn; in al &thorn;ing to kep ri&yogh;twisnes, &thorn;at he chalang only &thorn;is to him &thorn;at [he] knowi&thorn; to be of his ri&yogh;t, and ref not o&thorn;er mennis &thorn;ingis, ne touche; feel he him euyn wi&thorn; o&thorn;er. Also, in &thorn;e story of Seynt Clement is found, &thorn;at Petir<NOTE PLACE="marg">Clement.</NOTE> 
<PB REF="00000175.tif" N="111"> blamid Clementis modir begging, and seid sche schuld wirk wi&thorn; her handis. And also &thorn;at Clement Pope hadde writun be nam all &thorn;e nedy folk of &thorn;e cuntrees, and he &thorn;olid not hem to be soget vn to begry, &thorn;at &thorn;e clensing of baptem had halowid. Also bi lawe cyuil it is not leful to a mi&yogh;ty body to beg; &thorn;erfor be &thorn;ey war &thorn;eis vniust beggars, and ilk man se to wam he &yogh;eue almis, wat maner and whi, and wherof; for &thorn;us biddi&thorn; Crist, Wan &thorn;u makist a meyt<NOTE PLACE="marg">Luc. xix<SUP>o</SUP>.</NOTE> or sopar, calle &thorn;u not &thorn;i riche frendis, neybors, ne cosynis, &thorn;at &thorn;ei bid not &thorn;e a&yogh;en and reward be maad to &thorn;e. But calle &thorn;e pore, blynd, crokid, and feble, &thorn;at han not werof to quit &thorn;e, and &thorn;u schalt be blessid, and it schal be quit &thorn;ee in &thorn;e rising a&yogh;en of ri&yogh;tfulmen, for &thorn;ey may not. And God sei&thorn; bi &thorn;e wise man, If &thorn;u schalt do<NOTE PLACE="marg">Eccli. xij<SUP>o</SUP>.</NOTE> wel, wit to wam, and &thorn;er schal be mikil grace in &thorn;i goodis. Do wel to &thorn;e iust man, and &thorn;u schalt fynd reward of God, &thorn;ow &thorn;u fynd not of him. &yogh;eue to &thorn;e mercyful and reseyue not &thorn;e synnar; &yogh;ef to &thorn;e good, and to &thorn;e mek do wel, and &yogh;ef not to &thorn;e vnpitous; forbede &thorn;i louis to be &yogh;euen to him, &thorn;at he be not mi&yogh;tiar in hem &thorn;an &thorn;u. For &thorn;u schalt fynd double iuel in all goodis, &thorn;at &thorn;u dost to him; ffor God ha&thorn; synnars to hate, and he schal &yogh;eld veniaunce to &thorn;e wickid. And &thorn;us is also bedun, Wil &thorn;u not do almis of oker and vsur; &thorn;at is, do not swilk defautis to do almis &thorn;erof, ne hald &yogh;ow not clen &thorn;erof, but if we mak o&thorn;er dew satisfaccoun; ffor &thorn;e decre sei&thorn;, &THORN;e offring of wickid &thorn;ing is filid, for God approui&thorn; not<NOTE PLACE="marg">Decre.</NOTE> &thorn;e gestis of wickid men, nor he loki&thorn; not in to &thorn;e offring of &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg">Eccli. xxxiu<SUP>o</SUP>.</NOTE> vnpitous. Nor he schal not be merciful to synnis, in &thorn;e multitud of &thorn;er sacrifice. Bred of &thorn;e nedy is &thorn;e lif of &thorn;e pore; he &thorn;at de|fraudi&thorn; him, he is a man slear; he &thorn;at schedi&thorn; blud, and he &thorn;at do&thorn; fraud to &thorn;e hirid hyne are bre&thorn;er. Perchauns sum man &thorn;inki&thorn; it, are mani riche men auarous and couetous, I haue no synne if I tak it fro hem, and gif it to &thorn;e pore; I may geyt mede of &thorn;is, &thorn;at &thorn;ei do no good of. But &thorn;is &thorn;out is sterid to him bi sleyt of &thorn;e fend, for if a man gef al &thorn;at he took, &thorn;is is not to be wenid almis, 
<PB REF="00000176.tif" N="112"> if &thorn;is be &yogh;euen or despendid to &thorn;e pore &thorn;at is getun of leful &thorn;ingis. ffor he &thorn;at taki&thorn; iuel in &thorn;is entent &thorn;at he &yogh;eui&thorn; wel, he is more<NOTE PLACE="marg">Gregor.</NOTE> greuid &thorn;an helpid; &thorn;erfor &thorn;at we tak no &thorn;ing vnder color to do almis wi&thorn; synne, &thorn;e scripture for bedi&thorn;, seying, Offringis of wickid|<NOTE PLACE="marg">Prov. xxj<SUP>o</SUP>.</NOTE>men are abhominable, &thorn;at are offrid of felonie; he &thorn;at offri&thorn; sacrifice<NOTE PLACE="marg">Eccli. xxxiu<SUP>o</SUP>.</NOTE> of &thorn;e substaunce of &thorn;e pore, os he &thorn;at sle&thorn; &thorn;e sone in &thorn;e si&yogh;t of &thorn;e fadre. And wat &thorn;at is offrid in felony in &thorn;e sacrifice of God it softi&thorn; not, but steri&thorn; his wra&thorn;e. It semi&thorn; wel &thorn;at &thorn;eis vniust beggars, and namly &thorn;e ministers of &thorn;e kirk, brekyn &thorn;e bidding of God; ffor he biddi&thorn; &thorn;us, Vtterly a nedy man and beggar be not a<NOTE PLACE="marg">Deut. xu<SUP>o</SUP>.</NOTE> mong &yogh;owe; &thorn;at is to sey, &THORN;oli&thorn; not in &yogh;our defaut ani fal in to so gret nede, &thorn;at he be nedid to beg. And bi &thorn;e same ne man schuld blamfuly bi idulnes, bi rechlesnes, no&thorn;er bi wast, noi&thorn;er bi foly, bring him silf to swilk nede. And if he dede, men schuld not &yogh;eue to him &thorn;at he aski&thorn;, as is befor seid. And for Salamon sei&thorn;, &THORN;e<NOTE PLACE="marg">Prov. xx<SUP>o</SUP>.</NOTE> slowman wold not in winter here for &thorn;e cold; &thorn;erfor he schal beg in &thorn;e somer, and &thorn;er schal not be &yogh;euen to him. And if he beg wi&thorn; out nede, he do&thorn; vniustly; for to beg, is &thorn;e creater to schew be word or wark or tokun is defaut wanting, and nedi&thorn; to be releuid, and ask bi side &thorn;e titil of worldly dede, sum &thorn;ing to be releuid by; of &thorn;is need &thorn;an if he noi&thorn;er want, ne haue nede to be releuid, he do&thorn; vniustly &thorn;at breki&thorn; Goddis bidding, li&yogh;e&thorn;, and beri&thorn; falswitnes; ffor he affermi&thorn; &thorn;at ned is &thorn;er, wan it is not; and &thorn;us he is a &thorn;ef, and fraudful reuar. Also it semi&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;ei put wrong un to God, or to &thorn;e peple, or to bo&thorn;e; ffor &thorn;us is seid in Goddis lawe, &THORN;e wark|man is wor&thorn;i of his meed, and his hyre. And eft, who &thorn;at warki&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="marg">Matt. x<SUP>o</SUP>.</NOTE> ani &thorn;ing to &thorn;e, pay him his hyre a none. But wan &thorn;eis ministeris<NOTE PLACE="marg">Tobit. iu<SUP>o</SUP>.</NOTE> of &thorn;e wark han don &thorn;er office, if God or &thorn;e peple wil not pay hem &thorn;er hire, &thorn;an is God or &thorn;e peple vniust, if God schuld pay and do&thorn; not, he do&thorn; &thorn;an a&yogh;en his oune law. If &thorn;e pepul schuld pay, and do&thorn; not, &thorn;an &thorn;e peple breki&thorn; &thorn;e bidding of God. But if &thorn;eis men beggars are not sent of God, to do &thorn;is office, or do&thorn; not &thorn;is 
<PB REF="00000177.tif" N="113"> dede trewly, or ellis nedi&thorn; not to beg. And ellis &thorn;e peple is redy to quit hem &thorn;er seruice. But of &thorn;is wil &thorn;ei not be payid, but gredyly gon abowt to geyt al &thorn;at &thorn;ey may, &thorn;an &thorn;ei do uniustly, and silun God and &thorn;e peple. And &thorn;us may &thorn;ei dred in &thorn;is, lest &thorn;ei be childre of iudas gostly in maneris, and &thorn;e synful begging be despi|tously kast on hem, os is prayid in &thorn;e Salme, Wandring bi his sones borne, and beg &thorn;ey, cast out of &thorn;er dwellingis. For dred of &thorn;is schuld &thorn;eis meny be aferd to beg as &thorn;ei do, wyting wel &thorn;at Crist beggid not, but if he nedi&thorn;, ne seyntis noi&thorn;er. And if &thorn;ei dede, &thorn;ei repentid &thorn;er of and amendid; and so I rede &thorn;eis beggars do bi tyme, and come to Crist. Amen, Amen.</P>
